INSERT INTO `phpbb_weblog_entries` VALUES (1, 2, 0, 'Entry Number One', 'This is a sample blog entry\r\n\r\nThe intent of my posts were not to diminish the severity of the problem or to make light of\r\nthe suffering that you, your husband, and your friends had the unfortunate circumstance of\r\nenduring.  On the contrary, since hookworm disease in humans is no longer common in\r\nthis country, we seldom consider the possibility of infection, and most people don’t even\r\nknow what it is, therefore I wanted to share with the readers of this board some facts\r\nregarding the condition. \r\n\r\nFrankly Sara, you have done all of us a great service by posting your experience, because \r\nwe all should be aware of the potential danger.  I spent several years in Asia and on \r\nvarious Pacific islands when I was in my 20’s, and was aware of many tropical diseases\r\nincluding this one, but hookworm is not something I have given much thought when\r\ntraveling to Jamaica.  However, it would be wise to do so since the number of people in\r\nthe world affected by this parasite is estimated in the hundreds of millions.  That being\r\nsaid, I would like to attempt to dampen some of the fear engendered in people’s minds by\r\nthe thought of there being a nasty nematode waiting under the hammock.  It was for this\r\nreason that I made the statement that the condition is easily treated.  That is a statement\r\nfrom which I do not retreat.  Although you and your husband were sick from the\r\nmedication, there IS effective medical treatment available, and the course of treatment is\r\nrelatively short.  Although some discomfort is inevitable, it is nothing to compare with the\r\ndiscomfort from other maladies of the tropical third world such as malaria, cholera,\r\nnecrotizing bacterial infections of the skin, etc.\r\n\r\nOnce again, Sara, thank you for sharing your experiences with us.  Hopefully, your next\r\nvisit to Jamaica will be more pleasant and parasite free.  Also, hopefully we can now move\r\non to discussion of the more pleasant aspects of  Jamaican travel.', 'c0052d1fcb', 3, -1, '', 1151275950, 23, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 1, 3, 0, 0, '');
INSERT INTO `phpbb_weblog_entries` VALUES (2, 1, 0, 'Blog entry test 1', 'There once was a man with a parrot that swore like a sailor. I mean he''s a pistol. He can\r\nswear for five minutes straight without repeating himself. The trouble is that the guy who\r\nowns the parrot is a quiet, conservative type, and this bird''s foul mouth is driving him\r\ncrazy. \r\nOne day, it gets to be too much, so the guy grabs the bird by the throat, shakes him really\r\nhard, and yells, &quot;QUIT IT!&quot; But this just makes the bird mad and he swears more than\r\never. \r\nThen the guy gets mad and says, &quot;That''s it. I''ll get you.&quot; and locks the bird in a kitchen\r\ncabinet. \r\nThis really aggravates the bird and he claws and scratches, and when the guy finally lets\r\nhim out, the bird cuts loose with a stream of invective that would make a veteran sailor\r\nblush. \r\nAt that point, the guy is so mad that he throws the bird into the freezer. \r\nFor the first few seconds, there is a terrible din. The bird kicks and claws and thrashes.\r\nThen it suddenly goes very quiet. \r\nAt first the guy just waits, but then he starts to think that the bird may be hurt. After a\r\ncouple of minutes of silence, he''s so worried that he opens up the freezer door. \r\nThe bird calmly climbs onto the man''s outstretched arm and says, &quot;Awfully sorry about the\r\ntrouble I gave you. I''ll do my best to improve my vocabulary from now on.&quot; \r\nThe man is astounded. He can''t understand the transformation that has come over the\r\nparrot. \r\nThen the parrot says, &quot;By the way, what did the chicken do?&quot;', '5f2d111838', -1, -1, '', 1151276427, 20, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 2, 0, 2, 0, 0, '');
